Bring a large #pot{} of salted water to a boil. Wash and dry produce.

Trim @scallions{2} and cut whites into 1-inch pieces; thinly slice greens. Peel and mince or grate @garlic{1%clove}.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{1%tsp} in a large, preferably nonstick, pan over medium-high heat. Add @ground beef{10%ounce}; using a #spatula{}, press into an even layer. Season with a big pinch of @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch}; cook, undisturbed, until browned on bottom, ~{2-4%minutes}. Break up meat into pieces.

Add @red cabbage and carrot mix{4%ounce} and scallion whites; cook, stirring occasionally, until veggies are browned and tender and beef is cooked through, ~{2-4%minutes} more.

Stir in @pork ramen stock concentrate{1}, @sweet soy glaze{4%tablespoon}, and @water{1/4%cup}. Bring to a simmer; cook until thickened, ~{1%minute}. Turn off heat.

Once water is boiling, add @lo mein noodles{4.5%ounce} to #pot. Cook, stirring occasionally, until al dente, ~{5-7%minutes}.

Meanwhile, in a small #microwave-safe bowl{}, combine garlic, @sesame seeds{1%tablespoon}, half the @chili flakes{1%teaspoon}, 1 tsp oil, and a pinch of @salt{pinch}. Cover with #plastic wrap{}; microwave until fragrant, ~{30%seconds}.

> Use less chili flakes if you prefer less heat.

Once noodles are done, drain and transfer to pan with beef mixture; toss until noodles are thoroughly coated. Taste and season with @salt{} and @pepper{} if desired.

Divide beef lo mein between bowls; drizzle with garlic chili oil and sprinkle with scallion greens. Serve.

> Ground beef is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 160°.